---
import Button from "@components/ui/Button.astro";
// TypographyExample.astro
// Demonstrates all typography styles in the design system
---

<div class="py-16 md:py-24 mx-auto max-w-7xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 space-y-12">
  <!-- Eyebrow + Lead Combination Example -->
  <section class="space-y-8">
    <div class="text-eyebrow text-accent">Typography</div>
    <h1 class="text-h1 pb-2">Primary Heading (H1)</h1>
    <p class="text-lead">
      This is a lead paragraph following an H1 heading. It uses the
      <span class="font-mono text-small">text-lead</span> utility for introductory
      text that's slightly larger and optimized for reading flow.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is regular body text (<span class="font-mono text-small">text-p</span
      >) that demonstrates the visual relationship between your largest heading
      and body text. A good typography hierarchy helps guide readers through
      your content effectively while maintaining readability across different
      screen sizes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Eyebrow + H2 Combination Example -->
  <section class="space-y-8">
    <span class="text-eyebrow text-secondary">Typography Guide</span>
    <h2 class="text-h2">Secondary Heading (H2)</h2>
    <p>
      H2 headings are ideal for major section breaks within your content. This
      paragraph shows how body text pairs with your second-level heading. Notice
      how the size difference creates visual hierarchy while remaining
      proportional and balanced.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- New Typography Utilities Showcase -->
  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h3 class="text-h3 mb-6">Typography Utilities Showcase</h3>

    <div class="p-6 bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg border border-secondary/20 mb-6">
      <h4 class="text-h4 mb-2">Lead Text Example</h4>
      <p class="text-small text-secondary mb-4 font-mono">
        <code>bg-secondary/5</code> 路 Soft neutral ground for demo content
      </p>
      <p class="text-lead">
        This is a lead paragraph (<span class="font-mono text-small"
          >text-lead</span
        >) perfect for introductory text, article summaries, or important
        announcements. It's slightly larger than regular body text with
        optimized line height.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-6 bg-accent/5 rounded-lg border border-accent/20">
      <span class="text-eyebrow text-accent mb-2 block">Category Label</span>
      <p class="text-small text-accent mb-4 font-mono">
        <code>bg-accent/5</code> 路 Warm accent background for highlights
      </p>
      <p class="text-small font-mono mb-4">
        Class: <code>text-eyebrow text-accent</code>
      </p>
      <p>
        Eyebrow text (<span class="font-mono text-small">text-eyebrow</span>) is
        perfect for category labels, section identifiers, or small labels above
        headlines. It's automatically uppercase with letter spacing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h3 class="text-h3 mb-6">Tertiary Heading (H3)</h3>
    <p>
      H3 headings work well for subsections and important points. This
      accompanying paragraph demonstrates how your tertiary headings relate to
      standard body text. The contrast should be noticeable but not as dramatic
      as with higher-level headings.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h4 class="text-h4 mb-4">Fourth Level Heading (H4)</h4>
    <p>
      H4 headings provide further content organization for more detailed
      information. This paragraph shows the relationship between your
      fourth-level heading and normal paragraph text. At this level, the heading
      should still stand out while beginning to approach the text size.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h5 class="text-h5 mb-4">Fifth Level Heading (H5)</h5>
    <p>
      H5 headings are typically used for minor sections or callouts. This
      paragraph demonstrates how your fifth-level heading pairs with standard
      body text. The visual distinction becomes more subtle at this level, often
      relying on weight differences rather than dramatic size changes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h6 class="text-h6 mb-4">Sixth Level Heading (H6)</h6>
    <p>
      H6 headings represent your smallest heading size, useful for small details
      or specialized content. This paragraph shows how your smallest heading
      relates to normal paragraph text. At this level, the distinction is often
      minimal, with perhaps only font weight differentiating the heading.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <p class="text-quote italic">
      This is an example of a blockquote or featured text using the quote
      typography style. It should stand out from regular paragraphs while
      maintaining harmony with the overall typographic system.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-8">
    <p class="text-p mb-4">
      This is a standard paragraph (<span class="font-mono text-small"
        >text-p</span
      >) demonstrating your base text style. It should be highly readable and
      comfortable for extended reading.
    </p>
    <p class="text-smallall mb-6">
      This is small text (<span class="font-mono text-xs">text-smallall</span>)
      which might be used for captions, footnotes, or supplementary information.
    </p>
    <Button variant="solid" size="md">Button Text Style</Button>
  </section>

  <!-- Real-world Usage Examples -->
  <section class="space-y-12">
    <h3 class="text-h3 mb-6">Real-world Usage Patterns</h3>

    <div
      class="p-4 sm:p-6 lg:p-8 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-xs hover:shadow-md transition-shadow duration-300 ease-in-out mb-6"
    >
      <span class="text-eyebrow text-primary">Blog Post</span>
      <p class="text-small text-dark mb-4 font-mono">
        <code>bg-white</code> 路 Clean white background with shadow
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-h2 mb-6">How to Design Better Typography</h2>
      <p class="text-lead mb-6">
        Typography is the art and technique of arranging type to make written
        language readable, legible, and appealing when displayed.
      </p>
      <p>
        This combination shows eyebrow + headline + lead + body text - a common
        pattern in blog posts and articles for creating clear visual hierarchy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div
      class="p-4 sm:p-6 lg:p-8 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-xs hover:shadow-md transition-shadow duration-300 ease-in-out mb-6"
    >
      <span class="text-eyebrow text-secondary">Recipe Card</span>
      <p class="text-small text-dark mb-4 font-mono">
        <code>bg-white</code> 路 Clean white background with shadow
      </p>
      <h3 class="text-h3 mb-4">Classic Chocolate Chip Cookies</h3>
      <p class="text-small text-accent mb-4">
        Prep time: 15 mins | Cook time: 12 mins
      </p>
      <p>
        This shows how eyebrow text can categorize different types of content,
        while small text provides supplementary information like metadata.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-6">
      <p class="text-small font-mono">
        <strong>Available Utilities:</strong> text-h1, text-h2, text-h3, text-h4,
        text-h5, text-h6, text-p, text-lead, text-small, text-quote, text-eyebrow
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>
